03746nam a22004575i 9780773567870DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19991999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735678707 a10.1515/97807735678702doi  a(DE-B1597)656979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPT365.B64 ǂb M39 1999eb 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a141/.6/0943090341 aMayer, Paola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJena Romanticism and Its Appropriation of Jakob Böhme :bTheosophy, Hagiography, Literature /cPaola Mayer. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v2700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tJakob Böhme: His Thought and Early Reception -- tThe Seduction of Influence: A Forschungsbericht -- tBöhme’s Thought: A Précis -- tBohme’s Reception in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries: A Typology -- tJakob Böhme and the Jena Circle. The Story of a Reception -- t -- tThe Discovery: Ludwig Tieck -- tAn Interrupted Reception: Novalis -- tTowards A Mystical Science: J. W. Ritter -- tFrom Universalpoesie to Christian Idealism: Böhme ’s Thought and Philosophical Romanticism -- tThe Limits of the Reception: F.E.D. Schleiermacher, August Wilhelm, Caroline, and Dorothea Schlegel -- tUniversalpoesie, Mythology, and Christian Idealism: Friedrich Schlegel -- tIdealism, Human Freedom and the Problem of Evil: F.W.J. Schelling -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese appropriations fall into two main groups: those pertaining to the name Böhme or a life assigned to it, and those involving concepts or images from the mystic's oeuvre. The first group constituted an attempt to co-opt the aura of sanctity attached to portrayals of the poet-prophet in order to invest Romantic Poesie with the sacral standing of religion. The second group, exemplified by Friedrich Schlegel and Friedrich Schelling, involved the borrowing and radical redefinition of a few concepts and images from Böhme's work in the hope of bridging the gap between the abstract first principle of idealism and the personal God that became an emotional necessity for both thinkers. Jena Romanticism and Its Appropriation of Jakob Böhme treats the Romantic reception of Böhme as a striking example of how the past is appropriated and rewritten in the service of self-affirmation. Analysing the need and the techniques for this self-affirmation sheds light on the nature of the self to be affirmed and on the content and underlying motivation of the Romantic program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356787040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773567870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773567870/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles